Spurius Cassius, when consul, concluded the treaty with the Hernici, and afterwards proposed an agrarian law, the chief feature of which was the granting of a share in the distribution to the Latins. He was suspected of aiming at regal power, and was condemned to death. As in the stories of Sp. Maelius and M. Manlius, so in the account of Cassius many features have been introduced, which properly belong to the later agrarian struggles.
